{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c8043662-79a0-442b-8862-914dce25c695","content":"On macOS, the system automatically captures crash reports — no `createdump` needed:\n\n1. **Crash reports** are saved by `ReportCrash` to:\n   - `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (user apps)\n   - `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (system/root apps)\n\n2. Look for files named like `YourApp_<date>_<host>.ips` or `.crash`.\n\n3. You can also open **Console.app → Crash Reports** to browse them.\n\n4. For a core dump (for use with `lldb`), you may need to run:\n   ```\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n   before launching your app. Core files land in `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n**Quick check:**\n```bash\nls ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/ | grep -i <your-app-name>\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9991a7d5-80e3-4c48-bfb6-536cd7f6024c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps or crash reports for a NativeAOT app on macOS when `createdump` is not available. This is a knowledge question about macOS crash reporting mechanisms. I don't need to search the codebase for this - I can answer directly from knowledge.\n\nOn macOS, when an app crashes, the system automatically generates crash reports. Let me provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":329,"requestId":"C3D5:21BACA:1BFB641:1F94C9C:6A07C20F"},"id":"a193f751-611f-46ac-ba16-d3300d04459e","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:02:15.628Z","parentId":"6604cb64-33fd-4179-91d8-9978220ea529"}
